title: AREA ROUNDUP: Canandaigua boys soccer falls to Pittsford Sutherland
text: Posted Oct. 13, 2015 at 10:51 PM By Messenger Post Posted Oct. 13, 2015 at 10:51 PM Canandaigua, N.Y. CANANDAIGUA — The Pittsford Sutherland boys soccer team clinched first place in Monroe County Division 2 with a 2-0 win over Canandaigua on Tuesday. The two teams went into the half tied, but Sutherland scored two second-half goals to take control of the game. The loss is the Braves’ second to Sutherland this season. Cananadaigua lost to Sutherland 1-0 in Pittsford in September. Alex Grazulis made five saves for Sutherland (8-4-3), and Jarrett McWilliams made eight saves for Canandaigua (10-4-1). Canandaigua will play its final game of the regular season at Brighton. The Braves defeated Brighton 3-0 at home earlier this year. The game against the Barons is scheduled for a 7:30 p.m. start on Thursday. In other high school boys soccer action on Tuesday: Naples 9, Midlakes 1 The Big Green had eight different players score against the Screaming Eagles. Alex Arsenault scored two goals, Zack Dormer had a goal and three assists, and Conrad Rathbun added a goal and two assists. Nate Northrop and Jake Chapman combined in goal for the win. Midlakes’ (2-13) Josh Tubbs and Jeff Landuyt combined for eight saves. Naples (11-1-3) will play at Bloomfield and Midlakes will host Honeoye to end the season on Thursday. South Seneca/Romulus 2, Bloomfield 1 Lincoln Bachman-Lowe and Adam Wagner scored for SS/R and Wagner and Eli Corning each had an assist. Wyatt Conklin scored the lone goal for the Bombers. GIRLS SWIMMING Penfield 100, Victor 86 Natalie Zaravella won the 100 butterfly and 200 free and Mia Baggett won the 200 individual medley and the 100 breaststroke to lead the Blue Devils. Erin Norton won in diving with a score of 338.70. Pittsford 121, Canandaigua 59 Maddie Schaffer set a pool record in diving, Lindsay Stone set a pool record in the 500 free, and Pittsford also set pool records in the 200 and 400 free relays. Canandaigua’s Serica Hallstead set a school record in diving with a score of 298.50. GIRLS CROSS COUNTRY Mynderse 3-0, Penn Yan 2-1, Marion 1-2, Williamson 0-3 Erica Barbay finished in second, Olivia Baxter took fourth and Sarah Shaffer took fifth for Mynderse. Maci Nicholson finished in first place for Penn Yan. Alyson VanCamp took third place for Marion, and Williamson’s Mikala Steinmann finished in sixth place for the Marauders. Red Creek 3-0, Honeoye 2-1, Pal-Mac 1-2, Marcus Whitman 0-3 Sydney Beach took first place and Chloe Weaver finished in second place to lead Red Creek. Honeoye’s Mikayla Gullace placed third, Mikayla Bock took fourth and Tracy Stutzman finished in fifth place. Liz Hoffer finished in sixth for Pal-Mac, and Marcus Whitman’s Allie Harford finished in ninth. Page 2 of 2 - Canandaigua 4-0, Spencerport 3-1, Hilton 2-2, Brockport 1-3, Gates Chili 0-4 Clancy Rheude and Katie Cobos finished first and second for the Braves. Spencerport’s Sarah Rappleye placed third, and Hilton’s Makenna Bleier finished in fourth place. BOYS CROSS COUNTRY Mynderse 3-0, Williamson 2-1, Penn Yan 1-2, Marion 0-3 Jeremiah Carnicelli placed third and Hunter Brignall finished in fourth to lead Mynderse. Tyler Jones took first overall for Williamson and teammate JD Grell finished in fifth place. Peyton Silliman took seventh and Nick Kinsey took eighth for Penn Yan, and Marion’s Daniel Ferreri finished in second place. Marcus Whitman 3-0, Honeoye 2-1, Red Creek 1-2, Pal-Mac 0-3 Gabe Stash and Nate Mayton led Marcus Whitman with second- and third-place finishes. Jesse Hallett and Zach Erikson led Honeoye with fifth- and sixth-place finishes, and Red Creek’s Breandan Mantz finished in ninth place. Pal-Mac’s Ed Ely was the overall winner of the race. Brockport 4-0, Canandaigua 3-1, Hilton 2-2, Spencerport 1-3, Gates Chili 0-4 Erik LaCourt placed third and Alec Andrews placed fourth for Brockport. Scott Loforte placed first overall for Canandaigua, and Hilton’s Jacob Scheg took second place. Cole Viavattene placed fifth for Spencerport. GIRLS VOLLEYBALL Penn Yan 3, Geneva 1 The Mustangs (12-2) won the first game 26-24, the second game 25-20 and the fourth game 25-23. Emily Wunder had 14 kills and 17 digs, Sydney Bloom had 18 digs and Jess Covell had 16 digs for Penn Yan. Geneva’s Maggie Cunningham led the Panthers (7-4) with nine kills and 24 assists, and Ally Acquilano had 24 digs. Lyons 3, Marion 0 The Lions swept the Black Knights 25-19, 25-11 and 25-17. Lyons’ Teonna Jenkins had 13 aces and three kills. Autumn Hallock had 10 digs for Marion. GIRLS SOCCER South Seneca 3, Honeoye 2 Kelsey Shaulis scored the first two goals and Jenna McDonald scored the third goal for the Falcons. Ashton Allison and Jenna Robinson scored a goal each for Honeoye. MacKenzie Rudolph made 15 saves for the Bulldogs. By Messenger Post
